==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/me ‘zæ li ɔns/}}
*:Rhymes: [[dalliance]]

===Etymology 1===
French: ''més-'', bad + ''alliance'', alliance

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

#marriage with a person of inferior social position

===References===
"But if you marry the old count you will make his last days happy, and as widow of the Grand...the prince would no longer be making a mésalliance by marrying you." - Leo Tolstoy, ''War and Peace''

"It was an abominable thing that my grandmother should have been disinherited because she made what they called a mésalliance, though there was nothing to be said against her husband except that he was a Polish refugee who gave lessons for his bread." - George Eliot, ''Middlemarch''

"In England, a grocer's daughter would think she made a mésalliance by marrying a painter!" - William Makepeace Thackeray

